05467nam a22006975i 9781442657274DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20202001onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426572747 a10.3138/97814426572742doi  a(DE-B1597)551065  a(OCoLC)1163878306  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aKE3170b.F83 2004 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a344.7101/88/092231 aFudge, Judy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLabour Before the Law :bThe Regulation of Workers' Collective Action in Canada, 1900-1948 /cJudy Fudge, Eric Tucker. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (414 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCanadian Social History Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Courts and Conciliation: The Norms of Responsible Unionism, 1900-1906 -- t3. Accommodation and Coercion: The Rise of Industrial Voluntarism, 1907-1914 -- t4. Industrial Voluntarism Suspended, 1914-1918 -- t5. The Postwar Confrontation and the Restoration of Industrial Voluntarism, 1919-1925 -- t6. Industrial Voluntarism in a Prosperous Interregnum, 1925-1929 -- t7. Industrial Voluntarism in Distress: The Early Depression Years, 1929-1935 -- t8. Canada's New Deals for Labour, 1936-1939 -- t9. The Exhaustion of Industrial Voluntarism, 1939-1942 -- t10. Recognition and Responsibility: The Achievement of Industrial Pluralism, 1943-1948 -- t11. The Hegemony of Industrial Pluralism -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this groundbreaking study of the relations between workers and the state, Judy Fudge and Eric Tucker examine the legal regulation of workers' collective action from 1900 to 1948. They analyze the strikes, violent confrontations, lockouts, union organizing drives, legislative initiatives, and major judicial decisions that transformed the labour relations regime of liberal voluntarism, which prevailed in the later part of the nineteenth century, into industrial voluntarism, whose centrepiece was Mackenzie King's Industrial Disputes Investigation Act of 1907. This period was marked by coercion and compromise, as workers organized and fought to extend their rights against the profit oriented owners of capital, while the state struggled to define a labour regime that contained industrial conflict. The authors then trace the conflicts that eventually produced the industrial pluralism that Canadians have known in more recent years.By 1948 a detailed set of legal rules and procedures had evolved and achieved a hegemonic status that no prior legal regime had even approached. This regime has become so central to our everyday thinking about labour relations that one might be forgiven for thinking that everything that came earlier was, truly, before the law. But, as Labour Before the Law demonstrates, workers who acted collectively prior to 1948 often found themselves before the law, whether appearing before a magistrate charged with causing a disturbance, facing a superior court judge to oppose an injunction, or in front of a board appointed pursuant to a statutory scheme that was investigating a labour dispute and making recommendations for its resolution.The book is simultaneously a history of law, aspects of the state, trade unions and labouring people, and their interaction within the broad and shifting terrain of political economy. The authors are attentive to regional differences and sectoral divergences, and they attempt to address the fragmentation of class experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aLabor laws and legislationzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor unionsxLaw and legisla